Date: Thu 12 Jun 2003
From: James M. Wilson <IceAxe5@aol.com>
Source: Newsday.com, Associated Press report, Thu 12 Jun 2003 [edited]
<http://www.newsday.com/news/health/sns-ap-monkeypox-cdc,0,4857917.story?
coll=ny-health-headlines>

Wisconsin: Suspected case of human-to-human transmission of monkeypox
-------------------------------------------------
Health officials in Wisconsin said on Thu 12 Jun 2003 that a health care
worker may have contracted monkeypox from a human patient in what would be
the first known case of the disease spreading person-to-person in this
country. Wisconsin state epidemiologist Jeff Davis said monkeypox virus
hadn't yet been confirmed in the worker, but it was suspected and experts
were testing tissue specimens.
The announcement came a day after U.S. government moved aggressively to
contain the first outbreak of monkeypox in the Western Hemisphere by
prohibiting imports of African rodents, banning the sale of prairie dogs --
believed to have spread the virus to humans -- and recommending smallpox
shots for people exposed to monkeypox. The government also expanded its
search for infected prairie dogs to 15 states.
The smallpox vaccine can prevent monkeypox, an exotic African disease, up
to 2 weeks after exposure to the virus but is most effective in the first 4
days. "We're optimistic we can deliver the vaccine to these people in time
to do good," said Dr. David Fleming, the Center for Disease Control and
Prevention's deputy director for Public Health and Science.
As of Wed 11 Jun 2003, health officials had confirmed a total of 9 human
cases of the disease -- 4 in Wisconsin, 4 in Indiana, and one in Illinois.
54 possible cases had been reported -- 25 in Indiana, 17 in Wisconsin, 11
in Illinois, and one in New Jersey, CDC spokesman Tom Skinner said. No one
in the United States has died of the disease. Fleming said he is confident
the outbreak will be controlled.
"Monkeypox is a disease that is potentially transmissible from person to
person but at a fairly low level," he said. "I don't anticipate the same
kind of problem that we anticipate from SARS."
Fleming said the smallpox vaccine is 85 percent effective against
monkeypox. The smallpox vaccine is widely available because states stocked
up on it out of fear of bioterrorism. More than 37 000 health workers in
the United States have been vaccinated. The CDC said health care workers,
veterinarians, and family members who have cared for or had close contact
with infected people or animals should get vaccinations. The agency also
warned veterinarians and doctors to be on the lookout for the symptoms,
especially in owners of prairie dogs or exotic rodents from Africa.
About 40 out of every million people given the smallpox vaccine for the
first time will face a life-threatening injury, and one or 2 will die.
Still, the CDC is recommending vaccinations even for pregnant women,
children, and people with eczema -- for whom the vaccine is usually
discouraged -- who have been exposed to infected prairie dogs. "Because of
the real risk here ... we're recommending a somewhat aggressive approach of
who should get the vaccine," Fleming said.
[Byline: Daniel Yee]
--
James M Wilson, V, MD
Division of Integrated Biodefense
