Date: 12 Jun 2003
From: Thomas E. Walton <Thomas.e.walton@usda.gov>
Source: Official APHIS release [edited]
Subject: Emergency Management Warning 3: Monkeypox in the United States
-----------------------------------------------------
The Centers for Disease Control posted the following information on their
Monkeypox webpage regarding the trading of prairie dogs at swap meets.
Information on Prairie Dogs with Monkeypox that May Have Been Traded at
Swap Meets
For Immediate Release
A joint investigation with state and local officials in Illinois, the USDA,
and CDC is currently in the process of conducting contact tracings from
Phil's Pocket Pets, Villa Park, Illinois, where prairie dogs infected with
monkeypox may have been sold to numerous buyers in 15 states, including IL,
IN, OH, KY, WI, TX, SC, FL, TN, PA, MS, MA, MI, NJ, NY, since 15 Apr 2003.
The Illinois Department of Health is in the process of notifying state
health officials in states that may have received animals from this dealer.
CDC is recommending that states contact these buyers and inquire about
recent illnesses in humans or animals in the 30 days after purchase.
The dealer also sold animals at 3 animal swap meets since 15 Apr 2003.
These included sales by Phil Mobley (Phil's Pocket Pets) at Lee Watson's
Reptile Show in Schaumburg IL on 20 Apr, 3 May, and 18 May 2003, the
Midwest reptile show in Indianapolis, IN on 27 Apr and [day missing] May,
and the All Ohio Reptile Show in Columbus, OH on 19 Apr 2003. In addition,
a dealer from Wisconsin, Scott Knapp of SK Exotics, sold 3 prairie dogs
acquired from this IL dealer, including one to an unidentified man, at a
swap meet in Wausau, WI in early to mid May 2003.
Records for swap meet sales are not required, and there is no way to
identify persons who acquired animals from these dealers at these swap
meets. In addition, people at swap meets often handle animals without
purchasing them. Therefore, broad circulation of this information is
desirable to facilitate identification of all possible human infections.
Persons who purchased ANY animal from one of these dealers are encouraged
to contact their state health department.
The following link is to the Centers for Disease Control's Monkeypox webpage.
<http://www.cdc.gov/ncidod/monkeypox/index.htm>
Please forward this information to your federal, State, and industry
counterparts as necessary.
If you have any questions about this situation, please feel free to call
USDA, APHIS, VS, Emergency Programs at 800-940-6524, 301-734-8073, or
e-mail at EMOC@APHIS.USDA.GOV.
--
Thomas E. Walton
<Thomas.E.Walton@usda.gov>
